1.1 EDA¶

This is the exploratory analysis of the dataset and includes all the features shown in the (Features) notebook.

The EDA was done in parallel with model design process to minimize the influence analyzing manually analyzing the interaction between features might have had on our model design process.

Data selection¶

We have three target variables which we'll try to predict using in our following sections. They are shown here as:

  • target_loan_status: whether the loan applicant has defaulted on their loan (0 or 1)
  • pass_grade: the grade assigned to the loan by the "Lenders Club" (A,B,C,D etc.)
  • pass_interest_rate: the interest rate set for the loan (converted to float)

1.1.1 Correlation Matrix¶

In [10]:
importlib.reload(graph)
graph.render_corr_matrix_based_on_type(source_df.dropna(axis=1, how='any'))

Loan Status has strong correlation with:

  • Applicant FICO (credit) score
  • Term of the loan (longer loans are somewhat more to be defaulted on)
  • While the correlation with the zip_code is almost 0.4 it is not significant (other variables like grade, sub_grade and interest rate are not included in our model because they are calculated based on estimated loan risk, we could still include them if our goal is to verify the quality of "Lenders Club" estimates we chose not to include them to build a "clean" alternative model using the same source data).

Loan Grade and Interest Rate have significant correlations with a much larger number of variables:

  • Loan Term
  • Loan amount and installment size
  • FICO score
  • Loan purpose
  • Applicant income
  • Income verification status etc.

This would indicate that the Lenders Club is trying to use a large number of variables to determine the grade and interest rate but that those variables are not necessarily as useful at predicting the likelihood of default.

Because the datatypes of features vary we had to use different methods to measure the strength and significance of each pair:

- Chi-Squared Test: Assesses independence between two categorical variables.  For bool-bool pairs due to categorical nature.

- Point Biserial Correlation: Measures correlation between a binary and a continuous variable. For bool-numerical pairs to account for mixed data types.

- Spearman's Rank Correlation: Assesses monotonic relationship between two continuous variables. Used for numerical-numerical pairs (for non-normally distributed data).

Since the Chi-Squared test outputs an unbound statistic/value which can't be directly compared to  pointbiserialr or Spearman Rank we have converted them to a  ` Cramér's V:` value which is normalized between 0 and 1. This was done to make the values in the matrix more uniform however we must note that Cramér's V and Spearman's correlation coefficients are fundamentally different statistics and generally can't be directly compared.

The expected_return show the rate of return adjusted by the default rate. e.g. while almost 60% of all G grade loans are defaulted on you can still expect to make ~12% per year because the interest is very high. A grade loans tend to be relatively much less profitable despite the much lower risk.

importlib.reload(stats_utils)
source_df_include_bin = source_df[include_cols]
# Drop annual income outliers
source_df_include_bin = source_df_include_bin[source_df_include_bin["pass__annual_inc"] < 500000]

numerical_cols = source_df_include_bin.select_dtypes(include=['int64', 'float64']).columns
categorical_cols = source_df_include_bin.select_dtypes(include=['object', 'category']).columns

binned_df = pd.DataFrame()

# Bin numerical columns and add them to the new DataFrame with dynamic labels
for col in numerical_cols:
    if source_df_include_bin[col].nunique() < 5:
        # Treat as categorical, simply copy it over
        binned_df[f"{col}_binned"] = source_df_include_bin[col].astype("category")
    else:
        binned_df[f"{col}_binned"] = stats_utils.bin_and_label(source_df_include_bin[col],
                                                               num_bins=4)  # Adjust num_bins as needed
    binned_df[col] = source_df_include_bin[col]
# Add original categorical columns to the new DataFrame
for col in categorical_cols:
    binned_df[col] = source_df[col]
binned_df.dtypes
